<h2>Reverse</h2>


<p>
Now we will <em>reverse</em> our audio. We make the audio play backwards.
</p>
<ol>

<li>Record yourself saying ‚Äúthis is my voice the right way forward‚Äù
<li>Trim the silence and normalize the track 
    <ol>
    <li><strong><em>Highlight</em></strong> the silence
    <li>Press Backspace
    <li>Go to Effects -> Normalize
    </li> 
    </ol>
<li>Copy the part where you speak. You should have the same audio 2 times.
    <ol>
    <li>Highlight the part of the audio where you speak. 
    <li>Press 'Ctrl+C' 
    <li>Place your clicker at the end of the audio. 
    <li>Press 'Ctrl+V' 
    </ol>

<li>Now, highlight the <strong>copy</strong> of your voice. 
<li>Click <em>Effects -> Reverse</em>
<li>Play the audio to make sure it‚Äôs correct. 
</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
<p>
Now, we want to show you that the reverse effect is <strong>reversible</strong>. This means, if we apply the effect again,  we will get the original audio. Now:
</p>
<ol>

<li>Highlight your <strong>reversed</strong> audio. And make a copy 
<ol>
 
<li>Press 'Ctrl+C' 
 
<li>Place your clicker at the end of the audio. 
 
<li>Press 'Ctrl+V' 
</li> 
</ol>

<li>Highlight the 3rd copy of your original audio

<li>Click <em>Effects -> Reverse</em>
</li>
</ol>
